<mjml>
  <mj-head>
    <mj-style> h2,img,p { margin:0; } td{ padding-top:0 !important; } p {margin-bottom: 10px;}</mj-style>
    <mj-font name="Roboto" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto" />
    <mj-font name="Roboto+Serif" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto+Serif:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..144,100..900;1,8..144,100..900&display=swap" />
  </mj-head>
  <mj-body background-color="#f0f1f3">
    

    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
    
    <!-- Logo Header -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-spacer height="10px" />
      <mj-column padding="10px 12px 10px 12px" width="100%">
        <mj-spacer height="16px" />
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" css-class="light_img" width="150px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/logo.png" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" alt="" />
        
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 0px" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 2px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="
              font-size: 16px;
              line-height: 1.4;
            ">Every successful company has a turning point—a risk that paid off, a product that redefined an industry, or a decision that changed everything. However, not every story is one of triumph; some of the most valuable lessons come from the failures and missteps that shaped the business landscape.</p>

        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 0px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    
    <mj-spacer height="10px"></mj-spacer>

    <!-- Bussiness history -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_fsection" background-color="#ffffff" css-class="mj_fsection">
      <mj-column background-color="#ffffff" width="100%">
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px 8px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="white">
          <h2 style="
          color:#8C3321;
            text-align: left;
            letter-spacing:6px;
            border-bottom:2px solid #8C3321;
            text-transform:uppercase;
              font-size: 20px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 300;
              padding: 18px 8px 10px 8px;
              
            ">A genius CEO</h2> 
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
      <mj-image padding="10px 12px 24px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-dec-11-1.jpg" alt="A genius CEO" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Henry Singleton</h2>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          In the 1960s, when most CEOs were busy growing their companies the conventional way, <strong>Henry Singleton</strong> was already thinking differently. Singleton, the co-founder and long-time CEO of <strong>Teledyne Inc</strong>., took a small electronics company and turned it into a massive conglomerate. What set him apart were his unorthodox, often contrarian strategies.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Singleton’s story begins with his early fascination with technology. He graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy and then earned a degree in electrical engineering from MIT. But rather than settle for a predictable path, Singleton set out to make his mark in the business world. In 1960, alongside his business partner, George Kozmetsky, he founded Instrument Systems, which would later become Teledyne.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Acquisition strategy</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          While most executives were focused on organic growth, Singleton would grow Teledyne by <strong>acquiring undervalued businesses</strong>. Over the next few decades, he acquired more than 125 companies, each hand-picked for its potential to contribute to Teledyne’s bottom line. From aerospace to manufacturing, Singleton’s acquisitions spanned industries and allowed Teledyne to grow quickly while <strong>diversifying its risks</strong>.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          He had a knack for finding businesses with unrealized value. He saw potential in struggling or undervalued companies and knew exactly how to turn them around. For instance, when he took control of Teledyne, the company was small, but under his leadership, it grew into a Fortune 500 giant.</p>
          </mj-text>


          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Capital management</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          Singleton’s most remarkable move came in the 1980s when he conducted one of the boldest <strong>stock buybacks</strong> in corporate history. At a time when many CEOs would have been focused on reinvesting profits into growth, Singleton used Teledyne’s capital to buy back shares from the market. This move reduced the number of shares outstanding by 90%, driving up the value of the remaining shares and rewarding investors.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          <strong>Warren Buffett</strong>, known for his contrarian views on investing, praised Singleton’s mastery of capital allocation. In The Money Masters, Buffett singled out Singleton as one of the greatest CEOs of his time, calling his ability to make money “<strong>genius</strong>.”</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 22px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">Legacy</h2>
        </mj-text>
        
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          When Singleton retired in the late 1980s, Teledyne was a sprawling empire. The company’s revenue had skyrocketed from just $10 million in 1960 to over <strong>$3 billion by 1981</strong>. Singleton’s ability to navigate recessions, capitalize on market inefficiencies, and adapt to new opportunities became legendary.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4; filter: blur(5px)">
          But despite his massive success, Singleton remained a relatively quiet figure. He didn’t seek fame or accolades. Instead, he focused on building a business that would outlast him.</p>
          </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section> 

    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
  </mj-body>
</mjml>